##TOPIC: Flow how to spring boot working.


Controller::
......................................
@PostMapping
public Product addProduct(@RequestBody Product product) {

    return service.addProduct(product);
}
.......................................
Entity::

@Entity
@Table(name = "products")
public class Product

.......................................

STEP 1 → Client Sends Request

Example using curl:

curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/products \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-d '{
      "name":"Laptop",
      "description":"Gaming laptop",
      "price":75000,
      "stockQuantity":5,
      "category":"Electronics"
    }'

STEP 2 → HTTP Request Reaches Spring Boot

Spring Boot receives:

POST /products 

## With json body.

STEP3: spring Search Matching Controller Method.

$ Spring sees:
@PostMapping    // Handle HTTP POST request

$ Then endpoint becomes:

POST /products

>> Spring matches request to:

public Product addProduct(@RequestBody Product product)

STEP4: @RequestBody starts JSON Conversion.

Spring sees:
@RequestBody  ...... Convert incomming JSON into java object.

STEP5: Jackson Create Product Object.
Internally Spring uses:
Jackson:

Product product=new Product();

Using your default constructor:

public Product(){
}

STEP6: Jackson Calls Setters:

JSON:

{
   "name":"Laptop",
   "description":"Gaming laptop",
   "price":75000,
   "stockQuantity":5,
   "category":"Electronics"
}

## Jackson internally calls:

product.setName("Laptop");
product.setDescription("Gaming laptop");
product.setPrice(75000.0);
product.setStockQuantity(5);
product.setCategory("Electronics");

Note: Jackson uses setters to fill object values.

STEP7: Product Object Ready
Now Object Becomes:

Product {
   id = null,
   name = "Laptop",
   description = "Gaming laptop",
   price = 75000,
   stockQuantity = 5,
   category = "Electronics",
   createdAt = null
}

## WHY id IS NULL?

$ Because client did not send it.

Also:

@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)

means:

Database will auto-generate ID.

STEP8: Controller Received Object:

## Now controller method runs:

$$ public Product addProduct(Product product)

where:

product

already contains converted data.

STEP 9 → Controller Calls Service
$$ return service.addProduct(product);

STEP10: Service Layer Runs
Service method is :

    // Add Product
    public Product addProduct(Product product) {

        product.setCreatedAt(LocalDateTime.now());

        return repository.save(product);
    }
    
STEP 11 → createdAt Added

product.setCreatedAt(LocalDateTime.now());

Now object becomes:

Product {
   id = null,
   name = "Laptop",
   description = "Gaming laptop",
   price = 75000,
   stockQuantity = 5,
   category = "Electronics",
   createdAt = current time
}

STEP 12 → repository.save()
repository.save(product);

Now Spring Data JPA + Hibernate starts working.

STEP 13 → Hibernate Converts Object → SQL

Hibernate generates SQL:

insert into products
(name, description, price, stock_quantity, category, created_at)
values
('Laptop', 'Gaming laptop', 75000, 5, 'Electronics', current_time);

STEP 14 → MySQL Saves Data

Database inserts row.

MySQL auto-generates ID:

id	name	price
1	Laptop	75000

STEP 15 → Hibernate Returns Saved Object

After insert:

product.id = 1

Hibernate updates Java object with generated ID.

STEP 16 → Response Returned

Controller returns saved object.

Spring converts Java object → JSON.

Response:

{
   "id":1,
   "name":"Laptop",
   "description":"Gaming laptop",
   "price":75000,
   "stockQuantity":5,
   "category":"Electronics",
   "createdAt":"2026-05-27T18:30:00"
}

